Rallies and protests were yesterday staged across Southwest states to drum support for the South West Security Network (SWSN), code named ‘Operation Amotekun’ recently inaugurated by the governors of the six states in the geo-political zone, but declared illegal by the federal government. In Ogun State,  the planned nationwide solidarity rally for the establishment of the Operation Amotekun held amidst tight security led by police operatives alongside other sister agencies. Participants, which included members of the civil society organisations, such as the Committee for Defence of Human Rights (CDHR), Yoruba World Congress (YWC), Yoruba Council of Youths Worldwide (YCYW) and the National Association Nigerian Students (NANS) gathered at Panseke/Post Office axis of Abeokuta metropolis, the state capital venue of the rally as early as 8am for the rally which did not start until 11am. Some of the participants also carried placards bearing different inscriptions such as: ‘No Amotekun, No Hisbah!’, ‘Scrap Amotekun, scrap Nigeria’, ‘Every Yoruba is Amotekun’ and ‘Amotekun is here, end has come to our suffering’. Led by the state commissioner of police, Kenneth Ebrimson, security personnel which also included operatives of the Department of State Security Service (DSS) and the Nigerian Security and Civil Defence Corps (NSCDC) were fully on ground their large number to maintain law and order at the rally. Leadership of the protesters, which included the coordinator of the Amotekun Solidarity Rally in the state, Chief Olawale Taofeek, Chairman of Oodua United People’s Association, Ola Bello as well as the National Secretary of the Committee for the Defence of Human Rights (CDHR), Yinka Folarin among others, addressed participants at the rally. Speaking with journalists,  Ebrimson, insisted that the command had no prior knowledge of the rally, insisting that the police was never informed of any protest or rally in the state. 